			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I don't see the current mez immunity as a problem.  Enemies still have root, stealth and stun to kill mind sorcs with very little difficulty, and they will continue to do it way more frequently than mind sorcs kill anyone else.  Plus, in order to get the complete immunity, you have to go 45 mind, which loses you the AOE root...a very difficult thing to lose on a CC class that only has one other form of CC (compared to say, a healer, who has several more lines of CC plus heals armor and instas).  Hibs have group purge, which is a WAY bigger deal than mind sorc mez immunity in terms of group survival.  How long would it take a mind sorc to duplicate THAT effect using his immunity, and what's the chance the enemy would let him demez his entire group anyway?  And with only one form of AoE CC, even a totally immune sorc will frequently run into the situation where the AoE mez won't work because of the immunity timer...and that will be instadeath for the sorc regardless of whether he resists mez.   Sure, he's not mezzed, but what else is he going to do?  Single target demezz or amnesia opponents someone else rooted is about it...his nukes won't kill the enemy before he dies, and neither will his debuffs...Amnesia doesn't help if everyone else is mezzed and can't kill the target.  If almost ANY class can stun the sorc, or if any melee or stealth class can get up to the sorc in an RVR battle, in all but rare instances, the sorc will die.  With lots of baseline stuns, as well as snares and roots to play with hibs will have no trouble.  Same for mids.  Anyone here been ganked by a mid PAC healer+multi PBAOE group?  There's no defense, and entire groups are dead before the 11 sec stun wears off.  Mark my words, these changes are nice, but they are not going to make mind sorcs much more of an RvR force to be reckoned with, unless it's by tricking them to increase their numbers, and the immunity timer thwarts a large share of the effectiveness of that as well!  I predict that most sorcs will eventually go mind to provide crack for groups and pets for easy leveling, and then respec to body for RvR, and that's even WITH mez immunity as it is now.  Giving immunity to mez without anything to follow it up with once the opponents group purge is sort of perverse, if you think about it.
<br />

<br />
Fact of the matter is, these changes AS IS really aren't going to enhance sorc survivability in RVR much.  They'll make mind sorcs easier to get into groups (for the crack), and it will be easier to level soloing because of the added charm ability, but for RvR, I think losing the aoe root and gaining the mez immunity balances out in favor of keeping the AoE root EVEN IF the immunity is 100 percent.  If it's less than 100 percent, then it's really no contest...stay at 44 and keep the aoe root, or go body.  The mez reduction on the group will likely be pointless...the sorc will be dead long before the rest of the group gets free because of the reduction on the mez.   You'd have to be way more altruistic than I am to say "it's ok, as long as everyone else except me in my group got RPs for that last battle!" <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" /> )
<br />

<br />
Come down on the side of reducing the utility of the anti-mez buff if you want, but it was really the only thing that was going to significantly help sorcs survive at all better in RVR, and even that was debatable given the consequences of the loss of AoE root.  Make it less than total immunity, and no one will want it, period--the cost is just too high.
<br />

<br />
Tequitus</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
